<TITLE> Real and Bayern extend leads </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Real Madrid beat Recreativo Huelva 2-0 in the Primera Liga and Bayern Munich also extended their lead in the Bundesliga with a 3-0 victory over Nuremberg. Arsenal and Olympique Lyon reclaimed the top spots in England and France respectively. SPAIN Real Madrid extended their lead at the top of the Primera Liga to two points after second-half strikes from Ruud van Nistelrooy and Gonzalo Higuain earned them a 2-0 win at home to Recreativo Huelva on Sunday. Barcelona took advantage of slip-ups by Villarreal and Valencia to move up to second spot after Argentine forward Lionel Messi scored one and set up another as he steered the Catalans to a comfortable 3-0 win at home to Atletico Madrid. Real head the standings with 19 points from seven games, two clear of Barcelona and four ahead of Villarreal who slipped to a 3-2 defeat away to Osasuna. Valencia drop to fourth after Espanyol halted their five-match winning streak with a rare 2-1 comeback win. ENGLAND Arsenal beat Sunderland 3-2 to move back to the top of the Premier League after Robin van Persie scored the winner 10 minutes from time. Manchester United, who beat Wigan Athletic 4-0 on Saturday and led the table overnight, slipped back to second, with Manchester City consolidating their third place with their fifth straight home league win, 3-1 over Middlesbrough. Liverpool were just 90 seconds away from defeat when Fernando Torres scored with a header to force a 2-2 draw with Tottenham Hotspur, whose goals came from Robbie Keane. Chelsea scored for the first time in five league matches through Salomon Kalou to win 1-0 at Bolton Wanderers. Arsenal are on 22 points from eight matches, followed by United on 20 from nine and Manchester City, 19 from nine. Liverpool are fourth with 16 points from eight games. ITALY An 89th-minute Adrian Mutu penalty gave Fiorentina a 1-1 home draw with Juventus in Serie A on Sunday. AS Roma claimed a share of second place with Juventus following a 3-0 win at Parma, who had Bernardo Corradi sent off in the 26th minute for a second booking. The real beneficiaries of Juve's dropped points were champions Inter Milan, who are now three points clear at the top with 17 points from seven games courtesy of Saturday's 2-1 win over Napoli. Fiorentina are fourth with 13 points and remain unbeaten. GERMANY Bayern Munich moved five points clear at the top with a 3-0 home victory over Nuremberg -- the widest lead ever recorded in the Bundesliga after nine weeks. Luca Toni scored a goal in each half to bring his season's tally to eight. Bayern remain unbeaten with seven victories in nine league matches and lead the table with 23 points. Promoted Karlsruhe, on 18 points, replaced Schalke in second after defeating the previously unbeaten side 2-0. Werder Bremen moved into third place with their 3-1 victory at MSV Duisburg. VfB Stuttgart capped a miserable week by recording their third successive defeat, a 2-0 loss at home to Hanover 96. The champions were reduced to 10 men in the seventh minute when Fernando Meira was sent off for handling in front of his goal. FRANCE Olympique Lyon reclaimed top spot in Ligue 1 with a 3-1 win at Girondins Bordeaux on Sunday. The six-times French champions have 22 points from 10 games and lead Nancy, who have a game in hand, because they have scored more goals. Le Mans, 2-0 winners over Nice, are third with 19 and Bordeaux remain fourth on 18 points. NETHERLANDS Brazilian Afonso Alves hit a Dutch first division record seven goals for Heerenveen in their 9-0 thrashing of Heracles Almelo on Sunday. Feyenoord moved top with a 1-0 victory at Vitesse Arnhem and Siem de Jong scored in injury time for Ajax Amsterdam to salvage a point in a 2-2 draw at Sparta Rotterdam. Alves scored a hat-trick between the 10th and 18th minutes and added four more goals within nine minutes in the second half. Gerald Sibon scored the other two to complete the rout
